<A NAME="eolPage32"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<EFX_AUDITORS_OPINION>
<A NAME="FIS_AUDITORS_OPINION"></A>
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM
</FONT>
</B>
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_REPORTOFINDEPENDENTREGISTEREDPUB_123348">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Board of Directors and Stockholders
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc.:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. and subsidiaries (the Company) as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the related consolidated statements of earnings (loss) and comprehensive income (loss) and cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015.&#160; These consolidated financial statements are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management.&#160; Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these consolidated financial statements based on our audits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States).&#160; Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement.&#160; An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements.&#160; An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation.&#160; We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. and subsidiaries as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the results of their operations and their cash flows for each of the years in the three-year period ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The accompanying consolidated financial statements have been prepared assuming that the Company will continue as a going concern.&#160; As discussed in note 2 to the consolidated financial statements, the Company&#146;s credit facility expires on September&nbsp;30, 2016 and at present no agreement has been reached to refinance the debt, which raises substantial doubt about the Company&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern. Management&#146;s plan in regard to this matter is also described in note 2. The consolidated financial statements do not include any adjustments that might result from the outcome of this uncertainty.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We also have audited, in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States), Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, based on criteria established in
<I>
	Internal Control&#151;Integrated Framework (2013)
</I>
	issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (COSO), and our report dated March&nbsp;4, 2016 expressed an unqualified opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<TR>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	KPMG LLP
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>

<EFX_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT>
<A NAME="FIS_NOTES_TO_FINANCIAL_STATEMENT"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTES TO THE CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS
</FONT>
</B>
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_NOTESTOTHECONSOLIDATEDFINANCIALS_084839">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 1&#151;Business Operations
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	References in this document to &#147;we,&#148; &#147;us&#148; and &#147;our&#148; mean Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. and/or its wholly owned subsidiaries, as appropriate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We are a premier gaming and entertainment resort destination whose operations consist of:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Dover Downs Casino &#151; a 165,000-square foot casino complex featuring popular table games, including craps, roulette and card games such as blackjack, Spanish 21, baccarat, 3-card and pai gow poker, the latest in slot machine offerings, multi-player electronic table games, a poker room, a Race&nbsp;&amp; Sports Book operation, the Dover Downs&#146; Fire&nbsp;&amp; Ice Lounge, the Festival Buffet, Doc Magrogan&#146;s Oyster House, Frankie&#146;s Italian restaurant, as well as several bars, restaurants and four retail outlets;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Dover Downs Hotel and Conference Center &#151; a 500 room AAA Four Diamond hotel with a fine dining restaurant, full-service spa/salon, conference, banquet, ballroom and concert hall facilities; and
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT .5IN;TEXT-INDENT:-.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="SYMBOL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&#183;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:3.0PT;">
	&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
</FONT>
	Dover Downs Raceway &#151; a harness racing track with pari-mutuel wagering on live and simulcast horse races.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	All of our gaming operations are located at our entertainment complex in Dover, the capital of the State of Delaware.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. is a public holding company that has two wholly owned subsidiaries: Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc. and Dover Downs Gaming Management Corp.&#160; Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc. was incorporated in 1967 and began motorsports and harness racing operations in 1969.&#160; In June&nbsp;of 1994, legislation authorizing video lottery operations in the State of Delaware (the &#147;State&#148;) was adopted.&#160; Our casino operations began on December&nbsp;29, 1995.&#160; As a result of several restructurings, Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc. became a wholly owned subsidiary of Dover Motorsports,&nbsp;Inc. (formerly known as Dover Downs Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc.) (&#147;DVD&#148;), and became the operating entity for all of DVD&#146;s gaming operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. was incorporated in the State in December&nbsp;of 2001 as a wholly owned subsidiary of DVD.&#160; Effective March&nbsp;31, 2002, DVD completed a tax-free spin-off of its gaming operations by contributing 100% of the issued and outstanding common stock of Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc. to Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc., and subsequently distributing 100% of our issued and outstanding common stock to DVD stockholders.&#160; Immediately following the spin-off, Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. became an independent publicly traded company.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc. is authorized to conduct video lottery, sports wagering, table game and internet gaming operations as one of three &#147;Licensed Agents&#148; under the Delaware State Lottery Code.&#160; Licensing, administration and control of gaming operations in Delaware is under the Delaware State Lottery Office and Delaware&#146;s Department of Safety and Homeland Security, Division of Gaming Enforcement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Our license from the Delaware Harness Racing Commission (the &#147;Commission&#148;) to hold harness race meetings on our premises and to offer pari-mutuel wagering on live and simulcast horse races must be renewed on an annual basis.&#160; In order to maintain our gaming license, we are required to maintain our harness horse racing license.&#160; We have received an annual license from the Commission for the past 47 consecutive years and management believes that our relationship with the Commission remains good.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Due to the nature of our business activities, we are subject to various federal, state and local regulations.&#160; As part of our license arrangements, we are subject to various taxes and fees which are subject to change by the Delaware legislature.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In recent years, the mid-Atlantic region has experienced an unprecedented expansion in gaming venues and gaming offerings.&#160; This is having a significant adverse effect on our visitation numbers, our revenues and our profitability.&#160; Management has estimated that approximately 30% of our gaming win comes from Maryland patrons and approximately 61% of our Capital Club&#174; member gaming win comes from out of state patrons.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In June&nbsp;2012, the State enacted the Delaware Gaming Competitiveness Act of 2012 (the &#147;Act&#148;), under which Delaware&#146;s video lottery agents are authorized to offer, through their websites, internet versions of their table games (including poker and bingo) and video lottery offerings.&nbsp; All games remain under the control and operation of the Delaware Lottery.&nbsp; Revenues from the internet versions of table games and video lottery games are distributed generally pursuant to the formula currently applicable to those games physically located within our casino, with the exception that internet service provider costs are deducted first, and the Delaware Lottery retains the first $3.75 million of state-wide net proceeds.&nbsp; We began offering internet gaming in the fourth quarter of 2013; to date operating results from internet gaming have not been material. &nbsp;Internet lottery games are, at least initially, offered solely to persons located within the State of Delaware.&nbsp; This territorial limitation would not apply to gaming pursuant to an interstate compact, such as the one announced in February&nbsp;2014 between Delaware and Nevada.&nbsp; Internet gaming participation is limited to persons who meet the age requirements for equivalent non-internet games.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Act also eliminated the gaming license fee and restructured the table game license fee paid by video lottery agents to incentivize agents to make capital expenditures, spend on marketing and promotions, and make debt service payments.&#160; In June&nbsp;2012, we paid a $2,241,000 table game license fee, which was for the period July&nbsp;1, 2012 to June&nbsp;30, 2013.&#160; This fee decreased to $1,017,000 for the period July&nbsp;1, 2013 to June&nbsp;30, 2014 and has remained between $1,000,000 and $1,100,000 for each subsequent annual period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In July&nbsp;2013, the State enacted a bond and capital improvements bill which appropriated $8,000,000 to the Department of Finance to be used to offset increases in vendor costs that the three Delaware video lottery agents would otherwise pay for the period July&nbsp;1, 2013 to June&nbsp;30, 2014.&#160; The State used $875,000 of the amount appropriated to offset increases in our vendor costs.&#160; Additionally, the bill created a Lottery&nbsp;&amp; Gaming Study Commission responsible for examining the competitive marketplace confronting the Delaware gaming industry, including the business performance and business plans of existing lottery agents, the marketing efforts and investments made by Delaware video lottery agents, and the division of revenue from the video lottery, sports lottery, table games and internet gaming.&#160; The Commission&#146;s findings and recommendations were released in March&nbsp;2014 and included: the State sharing certain vendor costs that the three Delaware video lottery agents currently pay associated with slot machines; reducing the State&#146;s share of table game win; and eliminating the annual table game license fee.&#160; On July&nbsp;1, 2014, the Delaware legislature approved the vendor cost sharing recommendation on a permanent basis.&#160; Our video lottery vendor costs were reduced by approximately $3,909,000 and $1,950,000 during 2015 and 2014, respectively, as a result of the cost sharing arrangement.&#160; The recommendations to reduce the State&#146;s share of gross table game revenues and eliminate the table game license fee were not part of the legislation that was passed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The Commission reconvened in September&nbsp;2014 to consider previous and make further recommendations relative to the gaming industry.&#160; The Commission&#146;s findings and recommendations were released in January&nbsp;2015 and included: increasing the State&#146;s share of vendor costs associated with slot machines; eliminating the annual table game license fee; reducing the State&#146;s share of table game win; and providing each video lottery agent a credit of up to 5% of video lottery proceeds to be used for marketing expenditures and a credit of up to 5% of video lottery proceeds to be used for capital expenditures.&#160; Delaware State Senate Bill 30 was introduced in January&nbsp;2015 in order to implement the Commission&#146;s recommendations, but it was not released from the Senate Finance Committee for action.&nbsp; In January&nbsp;2016, Senate Bill 183 was introduced to phase in some of the Commission&#146;s recommendations over the next four years and to authorize internet sports betting in Delaware, but it has not been acted upon to date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Without legislative relief, we may be unable to refinance or extend the maturity of our credit facility on favorable terms or may default on our obligations, we may be unable to allocate sufficient resources to marketing and promotions in order to compete effectively in the regional marketplace, we may be unable to allocate sufficient resources to maintaining our facility, and we may be required to take other actions in order to manage expenses - especially with respect to operations that have operated at a loss, such as table games. &nbsp;Such actions could adversely affect our business, financial condition, operating results and cash flow.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 2&#151;Going Concern
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had a credit agreement with a bank group (see NOTE 6 &#151; Credit Facility). The maximum borrowing limit under the facility was $45,000,000 as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and the facility expires September&nbsp;30, 2016. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 there was $31,500,000 outstanding under the facility.&#160; The credit facility is classified as a current liability as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 in our consolidated balance sheets as the facility expires on September&nbsp;30, 2016.&#160; We will seek to refinance or extend the maturity of this obligation prior to its expiration date; however, there is no assurance that we will be able to execute this refinancing or extension or, if we are able to refinance or extend this obligation, that the terms of such refinancing or extension would be as favorable as the terms of our existing credit facility.&#160; These factors raise substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern.&nbsp; The accompanying financial statements have been prepared assuming that we will continue as a going concern and do not include any adjustments that might result from the outcome of this uncertainty.&#160; The report from our independent registered public accountants, KPMG LLP, dated March&nbsp;4, 2016, includes an explanatory paragraph related to our ability to continue as a going concern.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 3&#151;Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Basis of consolidation and presentation&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Dover Downs Gaming&nbsp;&amp; Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc. and its wholly owned subsidiaries.&#160; Intercompany transactions and balances have been eliminated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Accounts receivable&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Accounts receivable are stated at their estimated collectible amount and primarily consist of casino, hotel and other receivables which arise in the normal course of business.&#160; We issue credit in the form of &#147;markers&#148; to approved casino customers who are investigated as to their credit worthiness.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Investments&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Investments, which consist of mutual funds, are classified as available-for-sale and reported at fair-value in other assets in our consolidated balance sheets.&#160; Changes in fair value are reported in other comprehensive income (loss).&#160; See NOTE 9 &#151; Stockholders&#146; Equity and NOTE 10 &#151; Fair Value Measurements for further discussion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inventories&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Inventories consisting primarily of food, beverage and operating supplies are stated at the lower of cost or market with cost being determined on the first-in, first-out basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Property and equipment&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Property and equipment is stated at cost.&#160; Depreciation is provided for financial reporting purposes using the straight-line method over the following estimated useful lives:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Facilities
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="TOP" BGCOLOR="#CCEEFF" STYLE="BACKGROUND:#CCEEFF;PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:5.1%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	10-40 years
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="50%" VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:50.28%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Furniture, fixtures and equipment
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:5.1%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="44%" VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:44.62%;">
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	3-10 years
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We perform reviews for impairment of long-lived assets whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying value of an asset may not be recoverable.&#160; An impairment loss would be measured as the amount by which the carrying amount of the asset exceeds its fair value.&#160; Generally, fair value will be determined using valuation techniques such as the present value of future cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Income taxes&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Deferred income taxes are provided on all differences between the tax basis of assets and liabilities and their reported amounts in the consolidated financial statements based upon enacted statutory tax rates in effect at the balance sheet date.&#160; Tax years after 2011 remain open to examination for federal and state income tax purposes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Point loyalty program&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	We currently have a point loyalty program for our customers which allows them to earn points based on the volume of their gaming activity.&#160; All reward points earned by customers are expensed in the period they are earned.&#160; The estimated amount of points redeemable for cash is recorded as a reduction of gaming revenue and the estimated amount of points redeemable for services and merchandise is recorded as gaming expense.&#160; In determining the amount of the liability, which was $1,660,000 and $1,777,000, respectively, at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, we estimate a redemption rate, a cost of rewards to be offered and the mix of cash, goods and services for which reward points will be redeemed.&#160; We use historical data to estimate those amounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<A NAME="eolPage39"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Revenue and expense recognition&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Gaming revenues represent (i)&nbsp;the net win from slot machine, table games, internet gaming and sports wagering and (ii)&nbsp;commissions from pari-mutuel wagering.&#160; Other operating revenues consist of hotel rooms revenue, food and beverage sales and other miscellaneous income.&#160; Revenues do not include the retail amount of hotel rooms, food and beverage, and other miscellaneous goods and services provided without charge to customers as promotional items of $18,003,000, $18,241,000 and $19,905,000 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.&#160; The estimated direct cost of providing these items has been charged to the casino through interdepartmental allocations and is included in gaming expenses in the consolidated statements of earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	For the casino operations, the difference between the amount wagered by bettors and the amount paid out to bettors is referred to as the win.&#160; The win is included in the amount recorded in our consolidated financial statements as gaming revenue.&#160; The Delaware State Lottery Office sweeps the win from the casino operations, collects the State&#146;s share of the win and the amount due to the vendors under contract with the State who provide the slot machines and associated computer systems, collects the amount allocable to purses for harness horse racing and remits the remainder to us as our commission for acting as a Licensed Agent.&#160; Gaming expenses include the amounts collected by the State (i)&nbsp;for the State&#146;s share of the win, (ii)&nbsp;for remittance to the providers of the slot machines and associated computer systems, and (iii)&nbsp;for harness horse racing purses.&#160; We recognize revenues from sports wagering commissions when the event occurs.&#160; We recognize revenues from pari-mutuel commissions earned from live harness horse racing and importing of simulcast signals from other race tracks when the race occurs. Revenues from hotel rooms, food and beverage sales and other miscellaneous income are recognized at the time the service is provided.&#160; Amounts received in advance for hotel rooms, convention bookings and advance ticket sales are recorded as deferred revenue until the services are provided to the customer, at which point revenue is recognized.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Advertising costs&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	The cost of general advertising is charged to operations as incurred.&#160; Advertising expenses were $2,135,000, $2,171,000 and $2,209,000 in 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net earnings (loss) per common share&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	Nonvested share-based payment awards that include rights to dividends or dividend equivalents, whether paid or unpaid, are considered participating securities, and the two-class method of computing basic and diluted net earnings (loss) per common share (&#147;EPS&#148;)&#160; is applied for all periods presented.&#160; The following table sets forth the computation of EPS (in thousands, except per share amounts):
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">

</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:2.7%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</B>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	There were no options outstanding and we paid no dividends during 2015, 2014 or 2013.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Accounting for stock-based compensation&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	We recorded total stock-based compensation expense for our restricted stock awards of $375,000, $580,000 and $682,000 as general and administrative expenses for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.&#160; We recorded income tax (expense) benefit of ($20,000), $51,000 and $69,000 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively, related to our restricted stock awards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Use of estimates&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	The preparation of the accompanying consolidated financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make estimates and assumptions about future events.&#160; These estimates and the underlying assumptions affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, disclosures about contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the consolidated financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period.&#160; These estimates and assumptions are based on our best estimates and judgment.&#160; We evaluate our estimates and assumptions on an ongoing basis using historical experience and other factors, including the current economic environment, which we
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	39
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_39_002243_5796">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>

<A NAME="eolPage40"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	believe to be reasonable under the circumstances.&#160; We adjust such estimates and assumptions when facts and circumstances dictate.&#160; Volatility in credit and equity markets and declines in consumer spending have combined to increase the uncertainty inherent in such estimates and assumptions.&#160; As future events and their effects cannot be determined with precision, actual results could differ from these estimates.&#160; Changes in those estimates resulting from continuing changes in the economic environment will be reflected in the consolidated financial statements in future periods.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Segment information
</FONT>
</I>
	&#151;We account for operating segments based on those used for internal reporting to management.&#160; We report information under a single gaming and entertainment segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Recent accounting pronouncements&#151;
</FONT>
</I>
	In May&nbsp;2014, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;) issued Accounting Standards Update (&#147;ASU&#148;) No.&nbsp;2014-09,
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</I>
	, which provides a five step approach to be applied to all contracts with customers. ASU No.&nbsp;2014-09 also requires expanded disclosures about revenue recognition.&#160; This update is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017, including interim periods within those fiscal years.&nbsp;&nbsp;Early adoption is permitted for reporting periods beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are currently analyzing the impact of ASU No.&nbsp;2014-09 on our results of operations and, at this time, we are unable to determine the impact on the new standard, if any, on our consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In August&nbsp;2014, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2014-15,
<I>
	Presentation of Financial Statements&#151;Going Concern
</I>
	, to provide guidance on management&#146;s responsibility in evaluating whether there is substantial doubt about a company&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern and about related footnote disclosures.&#160; For each reporting period, management will be required to evaluate whether there are conditions or events that raise substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern within one year from the date the financial statements are issued.&#160; This update is effective for the annual period ending after December&nbsp;15, 2016, including interim periods within those fiscal years.&#160; Early application is permitted.&#160; The adoption of this accounting standard update is not expected to have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In April&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-03,
<I>
	Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs
</I>
	, which requires an entity to present debt issuance costs as a direct reduction from the carrying amount of the related debt liability on the balance sheet.&#160; In August&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-15,
<I>
	Presentation and Subsequent Measurement of Debt Issuance Costs Associated with Line-of-Credit Arrangements,
</I>
	which clarifies the treatment of debt issuance costs from line-of-credit arrangements after adoption of ASU 2015-03.&#160; The SEC Staff announced they would not object to an entity deferring and presenting debt issuance costs as an asset and subsequently amortizing the deferred debt issuance costs ratably over the term of the line-of-credit arrangement, regardless of whether there are any outstanding borrowings on the line-of-credit arrangement.&#160; The update requires retrospective application and represents a change in accounting principle.&#160; This update becomes effective January&nbsp;1, 2016.&#160; The adoption of this accounting standard update is not expected to have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In July&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued&#160; ASU No.&nbsp;2015-11,&nbsp;Inventory (Topic 330):
<I>
	Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory
</I>
	, which requires companies to measure inventory at lower of cost and net realizable value, versus lower of cost or market. Net realizable value is the estimated selling price in the ordinary course of business, less reasonably predictable costs of completion, disposal, and transportation. This update is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016, including interim periods within those fiscal years. The adoption of this accounting standard update is not expected to have an impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In November&nbsp;2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-17,
<I>
	Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxes
</I>
	, which requires companies to present deferred income tax assets and deferred income tax liabilities as noncurrent in a classified balance sheet instead of the current requirement to separate deferred income tax liabilities and assets into current and noncurrent amounts. ASU 2015-17 is effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016, including interim periods within those fiscal years.&#160; The adoption of this accounting standard update is not expected to have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 6&#151;Credit Facility
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On September&nbsp;14, 2015, we modified our credit agreement with our bank group.&#160; The credit facility was modified to:&#160; extend the maturity date to September&nbsp;30, 2016; adjust the maximum borrowing limit to $45,000,000 as of September&nbsp;14, 2015 and to $40,000,000 as of March&nbsp;31, 2016 through the date of maturity; and modify the required maximum ratio of funded debt to earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization (the &#147;leverage ratio&#148;), the minimum consolidated tangible net worth requirement and the minimum consolidated earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization requirement.&#160; The credit agreement also contains a minimum fixed charge coverage ratio. Material adverse changes in our results of operations could impact our ability to satisfy these requirements. Interest is based upon LIBOR plus a margin that varies between 150 and 350 basis points&nbsp;(200 basis points at December&nbsp;31, 2015) depending on the leverage ratio.&#160; The credit facility is secured by a mortgage on and security interest in all real and personal property owned by our wholly owned subsidiary Dover Downs,&nbsp;Inc.&#160;&#160;&#160; In addition, the credit agreement includes a material adverse change clause and prohibits the payment of dividends.&#160; The credit facility provides for seasonal funding needs, capital improvements and other general corporate purposes.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2015, there was $31,500,000 outstanding at a weighted average interest rate of 2.43% and $13,500,000 was available pursuant to the facility.&#160; Additionally, we were in compliance with all terms of the facility at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and we expect to be in compliance with the financial covenants and all other covenants for all measurement periods through September&nbsp;30, 2016, the expiration date of the facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.25PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The credit facility is classified as a current liability as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 in our consolidated balance sheets as the facility expires on September&nbsp;30, 2016.&#160; We will seek to refinance or extend the maturity of this obligation prior to its expiration date; however, there is no assurance that we will be able to execute this refinancing or extension or, if we are able to refinance or extend this obligation, that the terms of such refinancing or extension would be as favorable as the terms of our existing credit facility.&#160; These factors raise substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern.&nbsp; The accompanying financial statements have been prepared assuming that we will continue as a going concern and do not include any adjustments that might result from the outcome of this uncertainty.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

	41
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_41_003504_7056">
</A>
</P>

<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 8&#151;Pension Plans
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We maintain a non-contributory, tax qualified defined benefit pension plan that has been frozen since July&nbsp;2011.&#160; All of our full time employees were eligible to participate in this qualified pension plan.&#160; Benefits provided by our qualified pension plan were based on years of service and employees&#146; remuneration over their term of employment.&#160; Compensation earned by employees up to July&nbsp;31, 2011 is used for purposes of calculating benefits under our pension plan with no future benefit accruals after this date.&#160; Participants as of July&nbsp;31, 2011 continue to earn vesting credit with respect to their frozen accrued benefits as they continue to work.&#160; We also maintain a non-qualified, non-contributory defined benefit pension plan, the excess plan, for certain employees that has been frozen since July&nbsp;2011.&#160; This excess plan provided benefits that would otherwise be provided under the qualified pension plan but for maximum benefit and compensation limits applicable under federal tax law.&#160; The cost associated with the excess plan is determined using the same actuarial methods and assumptions as those used for our qualified pension plan. The assets for the excess plan aggregate $287,000 and $289,000 as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, and are recorded in other assets in our consolidated balance sheets (see NOTE 10 &#151; Fair Value Measurements).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">

</FONT>
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Historically, we have used a single weighted-average discount rate approach to determine the pension benefit obligation and the subsequent years&#146; interest cost component of the net periodic pension benefit.&#160; The weighted-average discount rate was determined by matching estimated benefit payment cash flows to a yield curve derived from long-term, high-quality corporate bond curves.&#160; This method represented the constant annual rate that would be required to discount all future benefit payments related to past service from the date of expected future payment to the measurement date.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we have elected to use a refined method, known as the spot rate approach, to determine the benefit obligation and the subsequent years&#146; interest cost component of the net periodic pension benefit.&#160; This method uses individual spot rates along the yield curve that correspond with the timing of each benefit payment and will provide a more precise measurement of the interest cost by improving the correlation between projected benefit cash flows and the corresponding spot yield curve rates. The change in method did not impact the December&nbsp;31, 2015 benefit obligation, but will result in a decrease in the interest component of the net periodic pension benefit starting in 2016. We have accounted for this as a change in estimate on a prospective basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	For 2015, we assumed a long-term rate of return on plan assets of 8.0%.&#160; In developing the 8.0% expected long-term rate of return assumption, we reviewed asset class return expectations and long-term inflation assumptions and considered our historical compounded return, which was consistent with our long-term rate of return assumption.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In 2014, we adopted the Society of Actuaries&#146; (&#147;SOA&#148;) RP-2014 mortality tables and MP-2014 mortality improvement tables to determine our December&nbsp;31, 2014 pension liability.&#160; These new mortality tables, along with a lower discount rate, resulted in the increase in the unfunded status of our pension plans and the increase in the accumulated other comprehensive loss at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&#160; During 2015, we reviewed the SOA tables and adopted the new updated MP-2015 mortality improvement tables which resulted in a decrease in our pension benefit obligation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Our investment goals are to achieve a combination of moderate growth of capital and income with moderate risk.&nbsp; Acceptable investment vehicles will include mutual funds, exchange-traded funds (ETFs), limited partnerships, and individual securities. Our target allocations for plan assets are 60% equities and 40% fixed income.&#160; Of the equity portion, 50% will be invested in passively managed securities using ETFs and the other 50% will be invested in actively managed investment vehicles.&#160; We address diversification by investing in mutual funds and ETFs which hold large, mid and small capitalization U.S. stocks, international (non-U.S.) equity, REITS, and real assets (consisting of inflation-linked bonds, real estate and natural resources).&nbsp; A sufficient percentage of investments will be readily marketable in order to be sold to fund benefit payment obligations as they become payable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	44
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_44_003134_9683">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We also maintain a non-elective, non-qualified supplemental executive retirement plan (&#147;SERP&#148;) which provides deferred compensation to certain highly compensated employees that approximates the value of benefits lost by the freezing of the pension plan which are not offset by our enhanced matching contribution in our 401(k)&nbsp; plan.&nbsp; The SERP is a discretionary defined contribution plan and contributions made to the SERP in any given year are not guaranteed and will be at the sole discretion of our Compensation and Stock Incentive Committee.&#160; During 2015, 2014 and 2013, we recorded expenses of $99,000, $126,000 and $120,000, respectively, related to the SERP.&#160; During 2015, 2014 and 2013, we contributed $126,000, $115,000 and $107,000 to the plan, respectively.&#160; The liability for SERP pension benefits was $97,000 and $124,000 as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We maintain a defined contribution 401(k)&nbsp;plan which permits participation by substantially all employees.&#160; Our matching contributions to the 401(k)&nbsp;plan were $874,000, $829,000 and $809,000 for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.
</FONT>

<A NAME="eolPage47"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The holders of common stock are entitled to one vote per share and the holders of our Class&nbsp;A common stock are entitled to 10 votes per share.&#160; There is no cumulative voting.&#160; Shares of Class&nbsp;A common stock are convertible at any time into our shares of common stock on a one-for-one basis at the option of the stockholder.&#160; Subject to rights of any preferred stockholder, holders of our common stock and Class&nbsp;A common stock are entitled to receive on a pro rata basis such dividends, if any, as may be declared from time to time by the Board of Directors out of funds legally available for that purpose.&#160; At the discretion of our Board of Directors, we may pay to the holders of common stock a cash dividend greater than the dividend, if any, paid to the holders of Class&nbsp;A common stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Under Delaware law, a change of ownership of a Licensed Agent will automatically terminate its license 90 days after the change of ownership occurs, unless the Director of the Delaware State Lottery Office determines after application to issue a new license to the new owners.&#160; Change of ownership may occur if any new individual or entity acquires, directly or indirectly, 10% or more of the Licensed Agent or if more than 20% of the legal or beneficial interest in the Licensed Agent is transferred, whether by direct or indirect means.&#160; The Commission may require extensive background investigations of any new owner acquiring a 10% or greater interest in a Licensed Agent, including criminal background checks.&#160; Accordingly, we have a restrictive legend on our shares of common stock which require that (a)&nbsp;any holders of common stock found to be disqualified or unsuitable or not possessing the qualifications required by any appropriate gaming authority could be required to dispose of such stock and (b)&nbsp;any holder of common stock intending to acquire 10% or more of our outstanding common stock must first obtain prior written approval from the Delaware State Lottery Office.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We adopted a stockholder rights plan in 2012. The rights are attached to and trade in tandem with our common stock and Class&nbsp;A common stock.&#160; Each right entitles the registered holder to purchase from us one share of common stock.&#160; The rights, unless earlier redeemed by our Board of Directors, will detach and trade separately from our common stock upon the occurrence of certain events such as the unsolicited acquisition by a third party of beneficial ownership of 10% or more of our outstanding combined common stock and Class&nbsp;A common stock or the announcement by a third party of the intent to commence a tender or exchange offer for 10% or more of our outstanding combined common stock and Class&nbsp;A common stock.&#160; After the rights have detached, the holders of such rights would generally have the ability to purchase such number of either shares of our common stock or stock of an acquirer of ours having a market value equal to twice the exercise price of the right being exercised, thereby causing substantial dilution to a person or group of persons attempting to acquire control of us.&#160; The rights may serve as a significant deterrent to unsolicited attempts to acquire control of us, including transactions involving a premium to the market price of our stock.&#160; This rights agreement expires on January&nbsp;1, 2022, unless earlier redeemed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On January&nbsp;18, 2016, we were notified by the New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) that the average closing price of our common stock had fallen below $1.00 per share over a period of 30 consecutive trading days, which is the minimum average share price for continued listing on the NYSE.&nbsp; Under NYSE rules, we have six months following receipt of the notification, subject to possible extension, to regain compliance with the minimum share price requirement or be subject to delisting.&nbsp; We will monitor the price for our common stock and will consider available options to resolve the deficiency and regain compliance with the NYSE listing standards.&nbsp; If we are not able to regain compliance, our stock will be delisted from trading on the NYSE.&nbsp; This would result in the need to find another market on which our stock can be listed or cause our stock to cease trading on an active market, which could result in a reduction in the liquidity for our stock and a reduction in demand for our stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.3PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On January&nbsp;23, 2013, our Board of Directors suspended the quarterly dividend.&#160; In addition, our credit facility prohibits the payment of dividends.&#160; See NOTE 6 &#151; Credit Facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.3PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	On October&nbsp;23, 2002, our Board of Directors authorized the repurchase of up to 3,000,000 shares of our outstanding common stock.&#160; The purchases may be made in the open market or in privately negotiated transactions as conditions warrant.&#160; The repurchase authorization has no expiration date, does not obligate us to acquire any specific number of shares and may be suspended at any time.&#160; No purchases of our equity securities were made pursuant to this authorization during 2015 or 2014.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had remaining repurchase authority of 1,653,333 shares.&#160; At present we are not permitted to make such purchases under our credit facility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_47_004705_5796">
</A>
</P>

	&nbsp;

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, we purchased and retired 73,453, 66,829 and 61,869 shares of our outstanding common stock for $65,000, $104,000 and $144,000, respectively.&#160; These purchases were made from employees in connection with the vesting of restricted stock awards under our stock incentive plan and were not pursuant to the aforementioned repurchase authorization.&#160; Since the vesting of a restricted stock award is a taxable event to our employees for which income tax withholding is required, the plan allows employees to surrender to us some of the shares that would otherwise have vested in satisfaction of their tax liability.&#160; The surrender of these shares is treated by us as a purchase of the shares.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.3PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	We have a stock incentive plan which provides for the grant of up to 2,000,000 shares of common stock to our officers and key employees through stock options and/or awards valued in whole or in part by reference to our common stock, such as nonvested restricted stock awards.&#160; Under the plan, nonvested restricted stock vests an aggregate of twenty percent each year beginning on the second anniversary date of the grant.&#160; The aggregate market value of the nonvested restricted stock at the date of issuance is being amortized on a straight-line basis over the six-year period.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, there were 1,411,410 shares available for granting options or stock awards.
</FONT>
</P>

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The aggregate market value of the nonvested restricted stock at the date of issuance is being amortized on a straight-line basis over the six-year service period or the service period remaining until normal retirement age, if shorter.&#160; The total fair value of shares vested during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 based on the weighted average grant date fair value was $608,000, $745,000 and $913,000, respectively.&#160; The grant-date fair value of restricted stock awards granted during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 was $0.89, $1.52 and $2.32, respectively.&#160; We recorded, within general and administrative expenses, compensation expense of $375,000, $580,000 and $682,000 related to restricted stock awards for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, respectively.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, there was $678,000 of total deferred compensation cost related to nonvested restricted stock awards granted to employees under our stock incentive plan.&#160; That cost is expected to be recognized over a weighted-average period of 3.3 years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 10&#151;Fair Value Measurements
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Our financial instruments are classified and disclosed in one of the following three categories:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 24.45PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Level 1: Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical, unrestricted assets or liabilities;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 24.45PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Level 2: Quoted prices in markets that are not active, or inputs which are observable, either directly or indirectly, for substantially the full term of the asset or liability;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT 24.45PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Level 3: Prices or valuation techniques that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable (i.e., supported by little or no market activity).
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
	48
<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_48_004931_2897">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:.25IN;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Our investments in available-for-sale securities consist of mutual funds.&#160; These investments are included in other assets on our consolidated balance sheets.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	The carrying amounts of other financial instruments reported in our consolidated balance sheets for current assets and current liabilities approximates their fair values because of the short maturity of these instruments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:18.1PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, there was $31,500,000 and $39,010,000, respectively, outstanding under our revolving credit agreement.&#160; The borrowings under our revolving credit agreement bear interest at the variable rate described in NOTE 6 &#151; Credit Facility and therefore we believe approximate fair value.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	NOTE 11&#151;Related Party Transactions
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013, we allocated costs of&#160; $1,851,000, $1,910,000 and $1,854,000, respectively to DVD, a company related through common ownership, for certain administrative and operating services, including leased space.&#160; DVD allocated certain administrative and operating service costs of $252,000, $240,000 and $220,000, respectively, to us for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, 2014 and 2013.&#160; The allocations were based on an analysis of each company&#146;s share of the costs.&#160; In connection with DVD&#146;s 2015, 2014 and 2013 NASCAR event weekends at Dover International Speedway, we provided certain services, primarily catering, for which DVD was invoiced $836,000, $689,000 and $801,000, respectively.&#160; Additionally, DVD invoiced us $230,000, $184,000 and $294,000, respectively, for tickets, their commission for suite catering and other services at DVD&#146;s 2015, 2014 and 2013 NASCAR event weekends at Dover International Speedway.&#160; As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, our consolidated balance sheet included a $44,000 payable to and a $22,000 receivable from DVD for the aforementioned items.&#160; We settled these items in January&nbsp;of 2016 and 2015.&#160; The net costs incurred by each company for these services are not necessarily indicative of the costs that would have been incurred if the companies had been unrelated entities and/or had otherwise independently managed these functions; however, management believes that these costs are reasonable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Prior to our spin-off from DVD in 2002, both companies shared certain real property in Dover, Delaware.&#160; At the time of the spin-off, some of this real property was transferred to us to ensure that the real property holdings of each company was aligned with its past uses and future business needs.&#160; During our harness racing season, we have historically used the 5/8-mile harness racing track that is located on DVD&#146;s property and is on the inside of its one-mile motorsports superspeedway.&#160; In order to continue this historic use, DVD granted a perpetual easement to the harness track to us at the time of the spin-off.&#160; This perpetual easement allows us to have exclusive use of the harness track during the period beginning November&nbsp;1 of each year and ending April&nbsp;30 of the following year, together with set up and tear down rights for the two weeks before and after such period.&#160; The easement requires that we maintain the harness track but does not require the payment of any rent.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:19.9PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	Various easements and agreements relative to access, utilities and parking have also been entered into between us and DVD relative to our respective Dover, Delaware facilities.&#160; DVD pays rent to us for the lease of its principal executive office space.&#160; We also allow DVD to use our indoor grandstands in connection with DVD&#146;s two annual motorsports weekends.&#160; We do not assess rent for this nominal use and may discontinue the use at our discretion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:20.3PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	In conjunction with the spin-off from DVD, we and DVD entered into various agreements that addressed the allocation of assets and liabilities between the two companies and that define the companies&#146; relationship after the separation.&#160; Among these are the Real Property Agreement and the Transition Support Services Agreement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<A NAME="A15-23447_110K_HTM_PB_49_005111_3020">
</A>
</P>
